nil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lacy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Lassy in Calvados, named from a Gaulish personal name <i>Lascius</i> (of uncertain origin and meaning) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lasee","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English or Irish   Lacy  ."]},{"name":"Lacey","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Lacy  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth de Lacy was born in 1271, in Devon, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Henry de Lacy. She had at least 2 sons with William de Beaumont I. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1271–":"1271–Surnud","1271–Female":"1271–Surnud","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1297–Male":"1297–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1268":"1268","ABT. 1297":"umbes 1297","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1271–":"1271–Kuollut","1271–Female":"1271–Kuollut","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1296–Male":"1296–Kuollut","1297–Male":"1297–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1268":"1268","ABT. 1297":"noin 1297","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1271–":"1271–Décédée","1271–Female":"1271–Décédée","1268–Male":"1268–Décédé","1296–Male":"1296–Décédé","1297–Male":"1297–Décédé","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1268":"1268","ABT. 1297":"environ 1297","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Everwyck, Angleterre","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Elizabeth de Lacy est née en 1271, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fille de Henry de Lacy. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec William de Beaumont I. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1271–":"1271–Verstorben","1271–Female":"1271–Verstorben","1268–Male":"1268–Verstorben","1296–Male":"1296–Verstorben","1297–Male":"1297–Verstorben","1250–Male":"1250–Verstorben","1268":"1268","ABT. 1297":"um 1297","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","York, Y